entry.title: Gracefully fail when CreateRequestHandler() is called twice

When PrefetchResponseReader::CreateRequestHandler() is called

for the second time, instead of CHECK()ing, gracefully fail by

returning null handler if `body_` is null for non-redirect cases.

gracefully falls back.



This CL leaves DumpWithoutCrashing() for investigating

the cause of crbug.com/1483599.

entry.title: [iOS] Fix username reuse checks for Password Bottom Sheet
entry.content:
This CL lazy initializes the "_usernamesWithSameDomainDict" member,

so that the password reuse check related data structure is properly

initialized.



Because [PasswordDetailsMediator initWithPasswords:...] receives a

potentially newly constructed IOSChromePasswordCheckManager object,

immediately initializing this structure can often happen too fast,

causing it to be initialized before the async process to fetch the

data from password stores has completed, which causes the

"_usernamesWithSameDomainDict" member to be empty, which causes the

username reuse checks to fail.



Bug: 1422351

entry.title: Prevent content analysis on web pages that don't accept drag and drop.
entry.content:
Before this patch, when a drag and drop operation ends, the browser

process determines if a content analysis is necessary and performs it

before sending any data to the renderer. Once the data reaches the

renderer process, the process determines whether the page accepts drops.

If not, the page is not given the data and Chrome performs some default

action, like opening a new tab. Since the page never receives the data,

there was no need to analyze it in the first place.



With this patch, the renderer returns to the browser the document's

requested drop operation as well as the renderer's final determination

of the drop operation. The latter, which is already returned and is

used to choose the visual representation of the drag, is used as

before. The former is used in the browser's drop handler to know if

the document is interested in the drop. If not, content analysis can

be skipped and the browser can perform its default action without giving

the data to the web page.



Note that even if the document expresses interest in the drop, it may

still choose not to handle it. In this case, chrome should still

perform any appropriate default action.



See design doc for detailed discussion:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1X9mUtD4gO8rdJBb81sGUCQoUDMsrYD71gLTplzOkQ-Q/edit

entry.title: Don't prefix-filter manual fallback suggestions.
entry.content:
Suggestions are filtered by prefix-matching against the triggering

field's value. http://crbug.com/1478986 explains why this shouldn't be

the case for suggestions triggered through manual fallbacks.



This CL makes this change by parameterizing ASG::

GetSuggestionsForProfiles() with the AutofillSuggestionTriggerSource.

Based on it, the correct field_content value can be passed to ASG::

GetProfilesToSuggest() and no filtering is applied for manual fallback

suggestions.

If the user starts typing after triggering manual fallback suggestions,

filtering is applied again, since this is treated as a separate

AskForValuesToFill() event, that regenerates the suggestions.



If a suggestion is selected, the triggering field's value is

overwritten. This is already the case due to the logic in the BAM.

If the triggering field is already autofilled, selecting a suggestion

only overwrites the triggering field's content, not the content of

other autofilled fields in the form. This is already the case too

and is not touched by this CL. An offline discussion with PMs confirmed

that this shouldn't change for manual fallbacks.

entry.title: Improve poor man's placeholder detection
entry.content:
Many websites rely on a pattern of label, where the

label is positioned by CSS on top of the input element. They morph the

label into a smaller version that is positioned on the top-left of the

input element when the user focuses the input element.



This CL relaxes the condition for Chrome to classify the label as a

label: Instead of demanding that the label is positioned fully within

the input element, it is now sufficient to overlap the input element.

This fixes for example the field detection in irctc.co.in.



Chrome on iOS does not have this type of label inference yet. So that

should be added by a separate CL.

entry.title: [Autofill] Eliminate AutofillAgent::focused_node_was_last_clicked_
entry.content:
This CL refactors AutofillAgent::focused_node_was_last_clicked_

to a parameter of AutofillAgent::HandleFocusChangeComplete().



There is one potential case where this is not equivalent: consider

the following sequence of events on non-Android:



1. DidReceiveLeftMouseDownOrGestureTapInNode()

2. HandleFocusChangeComplete() (called by some other event)

3. DidCompleteFocusChangeInFrame()



Before this CL, Step 2 set focused_node_was_last_clicked_ = false

and thus made Step 3 essentially a no-op.



After this CL, Step 3 shows the prompt.



We're not sure such a sequence of events is even possible. After

staring at the debugger a little bit, I think it may not be possible,

but these events look complicated with little documentation.



We've decided to land the CL nonetheless because it doesn't seem

too risky (in the worst case, the CL displays a few Autofill popups

that shouldn't be shown) and simplifies AutofillAgent a little bit.

out-of-range), or they are allowed not to; this is an implementation

detail. glibc does not, so none of our code can rely on it being

set. However, without knowing, the compiler is not allowed to substitute

an intrinsic for a math function, which means that very cheap operations

such as round-and-convert-to-int (lrintf()) become library calls

instead of single instructions. (See e.g.

https://gcc.gnu.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=48139.)



Enable -fno-math-errno across all builds, since we do not need this

behavior. This makes several functions become slightly smaller;

the full Chrome binary becomes slightly larger due to more inlining

and unrolling, but e.g. content_shell on Linux loses ~15 kB .text.

Some random examples comparing before and after, across various modules

on Linux 64-bit x86:



SkMatrix::setRotate(float, float, float): 204 → 199 bytes

(calls to sinf and cosf are combined into one sincosf() call)

xnn_init_qu8_add_minmax_avx512_params.cfi: 633 → 556 bytes

(same)

blink::Color::Dark() const: 570 → 552 bytes

(call to lrintf gets replaced with cvtss2si, surrounding code

gets better due to no need to save registers for the call)

stereo_itheta: 575 → 471 bytes

(calls to sqrtf get replaced with vectorized sqrtps;

interestingly, there were already sqrtss instructions generated

in addition to the calls)

chrome_pdf::draw_utils::ShadowMatrix::ShadowMatrix(unsigned int,

double, unsigned int): 770 → 728 bytes

(the old code to take into account that the “this” pointer may

alias errno_location, since its first member is an uint32_t,

and thus reload more values from memory!)



And some examples of increases:



tflite::ops::builtin::lstm::Eval(TfLiteContext*, TfLiteNode*) [clone

.cfi]: 29165 → 32498 bytes (seems to be more unrolling)

aom_denoise_and_model_run: 25942 → 26090 bytes (replacement of

sqrt() call with sqrtsd/sqrtpd instruction makes for more

aggressive vectorization, which takes more space)



Android binary size is unchanged, for unknown reasons (perhaps Bionic

already sets this flag?). MotionMark (both on M1 and linux-perf)

is in the noise.

entry.title: iwa: Keep track of opened response body producers
entry.content:
Short introduction:

When we read response body from a signed web bundle, the reader doesn't

need to parse it. This allows the caller of the reader to read the

response body directly from the signed web bundle file. Access to the

response body on reader side is provided by DataPipeProducer.



Before this CL the instances of the DataPipeProducer are self owned

and get deleted (and close the file) in the callback after the

reading has been completed. This means that the reader doesn't know

if the file is still being read or not.



After this CL the reader will keep track of the DataPipeProducer

instances. This allows the reader to know when the reading is

completed and the signed web bundle file may be removed

(when there are not active producers).



Besides that the web_bundle_file_data_source{.h, .cc} files were

deleted as we switch to the standard mojo::FileDataSource.

entry.title: Remove use_last_valid parameter from DeviceAuthenticator::Authenticate
entry.content:
This CL is part of a bigger refactoring process of the

DeviceAuthenticator class.



This parameter was a workaround to tell DeviceAuthenticator whether

the authentication validity period should be 0 seconds or not (i.e.

require re-authentication immediately or not).



Now, we can specify the authentication validity period directly to

ChromeDeviceAuthenticatorCommon, and we don't need to use this

workaround anymore.



A future CL will completely delete the Authenticate method, as it

doesn't have anything special anymore compare to

AuthenticateWithMessage .
